WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.260 --> 00:00:04.593
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:05.470 --> 00:00:06.470


00:00:07.070 --> 00:00:07.350
&gt;&gt; Our author this afternoon
is James McGrath Morris

00:00:10.190 --> 00:00:13.256
and I for one am very
excited to hear from him.

00:00:13.800 --> 00:00:14.316
As you may know, the news business
is undergoing some soul searching

00:00:17.750 --> 00:00:22.350
and some financial distress, and so
it's gratifying to talk to someone

00:00:22.420 --> 00:00:22.650
who has had so much success
writing about journalism

00:00:25.590 --> 00:00:27.390
and about the news business

00:00:27.590 --> 00:00:28.650
and the very interesting
characters that have built it.

00:00:30.130 --> 00:00:34.396
His books include The Rose Man of
Sing Sing: A True Tale of Life,

00:00:34.620 --> 00:00:35.116
Murder, and Redemption in the
Age of Yellow Journalism as well

00:00:38.190 --> 00:00:41.790
as Jailhouse Journalism: The
Fourth Estate Behind Bars.

00:00:42.090 --> 00:00:42.276
The book he'll be discussing today
is his most recent work Pulitzer:

00:00:46.370 --> 00:00:48.770
A Life in Politics,
Print, and Power.

00:00:49.980 --> 00:00:50.563
It is my great pleasure to
give you James McGrath Morris.

00:00:53.130 --> 00:00:54.130
[ Applause ]

00:00:57.620 --> 00:00:59.153
&gt;&gt; Thank you very much.

00:01:00.210 --> 00:01:00.433
About six months ago, I was
doing what authors usually do

00:01:03.720 --> 00:01:05.720
which is travel to small towns

00:01:06.070 --> 00:01:06.373
because there are people
who buy and read books.

00:01:08.900 --> 00:01:09.070
And I was in a bookstore where a
really kind reader felt my pain

00:01:12.930 --> 00:01:15.130
and asked me a softball question.

00:01:16.770 --> 00:01:16.986
So he said to me, "You spent five
years studying this guy's life.

00:01:20.820 --> 00:01:24.953
Is there any kind of practical
thing that you learned from it?"

00:01:25.670 --> 00:01:29.203
I thought, had mumbled some
sort of incoherent answer.

00:01:29.890 --> 00:01:32.556
Well, six months later
I have the answer.

00:01:32.560 --> 00:01:33.160
So if he's out there,
here's the answer.

00:01:34.560 --> 00:01:37.093
And if you wanna take
notes, feel free.

00:01:37.390 --> 00:01:41.990
The answer is if you make a lot of
money in life and you endow a prize

00:01:44.520 --> 00:01:47.720
like Pulitzer did,
everybody will know the prize,

00:01:48.480 --> 00:01:48.600
but they will not remember
who the heck you were.

00:01:51.560 --> 00:01:55.560
And for me as an author, this
actually gave me an opportunity

00:01:57.090 --> 00:02:01.156
because there are a lot of giants
in the 19th century, Morgan,

00:02:04.130 --> 00:02:07.330
Rockefeller, and we think
they have no connection

00:02:08.260 --> 00:02:09.993
to our lives, but they do.

00:02:10.420 --> 00:02:14.153
Most of you drove an oil-powered
automobile to come here.

00:02:15.060 --> 00:02:15.193
We're talking about Rockefeller.

00:02:17.060 --> 00:02:18.156
Many of you are hopefully
gonna run over and buy a book,

00:02:19.630 --> 00:02:20.083
and you're gonna whip out a
credit card which is based

00:02:22.710 --> 00:02:25.376
on a financial system
invented by Morgan.

00:02:26.510 --> 00:02:30.510
Well, Pulitzer is one of those
geniuses from the 19th century

00:02:31.540 --> 00:02:31.753
who is the midwife of the modern
mass media who, in a sense,

00:02:35.260 --> 00:02:36.993
may have brought you here.

00:02:37.260 --> 00:02:38.393
You learned about the
event maybe electronically

00:02:39.260 --> 00:02:40.140
on the Washington Post
website but this whole notion

00:02:41.780 --> 00:02:45.713
of disseminating news and all
of those things are owed to us

00:02:45.960 --> 00:02:47.826
or came to us from Pulitzer.

00:02:48.800 --> 00:02:49.090
And so for me as an author,
it's a great opportunity

00:02:51.910 --> 00:02:52.766
because here I'm writing about one
of the giants of the 19th century

00:02:55.520 --> 00:02:57.853
who most people knew nothing about.

00:02:58.310 --> 00:02:58.970
So unlike reading about
Morgan or Rockefeller,

00:03:00.650 --> 00:03:01.673
everytime you turn the page
it's an opportunity for me

00:03:03.160 --> 00:03:04.893
to tell you something new.

00:03:05.160 --> 00:03:05.640
So I wanna leave you with a couple
of aspects of why Pulitzer is

00:03:08.880 --> 00:03:09.003
so important to us, how, in a
sense, his hand is still reaching

00:03:12.890 --> 00:03:12.896
out through the grave and
touching our lives today

00:03:16.150 --> 00:03:16.550
and affecting the way
we communicate,

00:03:18.150 --> 00:03:19.816
the way we organize news.

00:03:20.150 --> 00:03:20.683
And I'm not gonna tell
you an old story

00:03:22.150 --> 00:03:24.000
about Pulitzer who'd start off
life as a Hungarian immigrant,

00:03:24.300 --> 00:03:24.500
came here as a mercenary soldier.

00:03:26.300 --> 00:03:27.496
I wanna tell you about how
he reshaped journalism which,

00:03:28.770 --> 00:03:32.236
in a sense, was a boring
craft before the man arrived

00:03:32.310 --> 00:03:33.576
and changed things.

00:03:34.310 --> 00:03:36.843
And the first seminal
moment is in 1878

00:03:37.510 --> 00:03:42.176
when he invests his last few dollars
in buying a bankrupt evening paper

00:03:42.870 --> 00:03:43.680
in the City of Saint Louis on the
steps of the Saint Louis courthouse,

00:03:46.660 --> 00:03:46.803
the same courthouse that
decided the Dred Scott decision.

00:03:50.250 --> 00:03:50.346
And all his friends think he's
nuts, an afternoon paper in a city

00:03:54.420 --> 00:03:55.130
where three afternoon
papers are being published,

00:03:56.910 --> 00:03:57.030
none of which are making money
and he's buying a bankrupt paper.

00:04:00.990 --> 00:04:01.993
And this is one of the
distinguishing moments in his life

00:04:03.720 --> 00:04:04.116
that will reflect the
characteristics that caused him

00:04:06.790 --> 00:04:10.190
to reshape our society
because he's not an inventor.

00:04:11.080 --> 00:04:11.433
He's not like Bell or somebody
who said, "Gee, we need a gadget

00:04:14.860 --> 00:04:17.060
where we can talk to each other."

00:04:17.790 --> 00:04:21.656
What he was is a man who could
perceive huge social trends,

00:04:22.880 --> 00:04:26.080
sort of like the Tuckfield
[phonetic] did before.

00:04:26.510 --> 00:04:27.000
And the analogy I give and people
think I've really lost my marbles

00:04:30.420 --> 00:04:31.150
when I suddenly asked you to imagine
a surfer, and here I'm talking

00:04:34.090 --> 00:04:35.956
about a 19th century figure.

00:04:36.090 --> 00:04:37.276
But I want you to see this
before I talk about Pulitzer.

00:04:38.570 --> 00:04:40.093
If you've ever been to the coast
where there are surfers and you look

00:04:41.580 --> 00:04:45.513
out on the waves, far past the
waves where they're breaking,

00:04:46.030 --> 00:04:46.300
they'll be young men and
women on their boards

00:04:48.760 --> 00:04:49.226
and they're probably
old surfers, too.

00:04:50.760 --> 00:04:51.430
Let's just say, men and
women on their boards.

00:04:53.090 --> 00:04:57.490
And they're paddling very slowly
and suddenly they paddle furiously

00:04:58.290 --> 00:05:00.690
and they ride a huge
wave that forms.

00:05:01.590 --> 00:05:06.123
Somehow, those good surfers are able
to detect the slight undulations

00:05:06.570 --> 00:05:09.503
in the water and realize
that's the big wave.

00:05:10.430 --> 00:05:10.663
Pulitzer did that with our society.

00:05:12.530 --> 00:05:15.263
Here he was in Saint
Louis and he realized

00:05:15.580 --> 00:05:15.826
that farmers were leaving their
farms in Illinois and Missouri

00:05:19.400 --> 00:05:19.520
and coming to the city
because of industrialization.

00:05:22.680 --> 00:05:22.723
They were becoming factory workers.

00:05:24.970 --> 00:05:26.570
So what were they doing?

00:05:26.970 --> 00:05:28.303
They were commuting.

00:05:28.970 --> 00:05:30.120
Women who used to be important
economic decision makers

00:05:31.420 --> 00:05:34.153
on the farms were now
becoming housewives.

00:05:35.080 --> 00:05:36.090
It's all gonna play into something
you're gonna see in a second.

00:05:38.270 --> 00:05:38.353
Gaslight and electric light allowed
people to entertain themselves

00:05:42.520 --> 00:05:44.253
in the evening by reading.

00:05:44.760 --> 00:05:47.693
A new printing press
had been invented by Hoe

00:05:48.370 --> 00:05:50.503
that could print papers quickly.

00:05:50.990 --> 00:05:51.730
Paper was being made from trees
that had the tensile strength to go

00:05:54.650 --> 00:05:57.050
through these machines at high speed

00:05:57.520 --> 00:06:00.053
and the Victorian Internet
had arrived.

00:06:00.360 --> 00:06:00.596
You call it the telegraph bringing
news from New York and Washington

00:06:04.590 --> 00:06:04.830
to Saint Louis as fresh
as that morning.

00:06:06.950 --> 00:06:06.966
So he took all of these ingredients
and published an afternoon paper

00:06:11.400 --> 00:06:11.770
with news from Washington and New
York as fresh as that morning,

00:06:15.230 --> 00:06:15.426
sold it to commuters heading home
desperate for entertainment filled

00:06:19.500 --> 00:06:21.966
with entertaining tales
about the city

00:06:22.470 --> 00:06:22.543
and economic decision making
material for the housewives,

00:06:26.130 --> 00:06:30.596
advertisements, where can you buy
gingham, where can you buy flower.

00:06:30.870 --> 00:06:31.456
And as a result, he created this
new medium of mass communication

00:06:34.550 --> 00:06:37.283
in Saint Louis that
became a huge success.

00:06:39.500 --> 00:06:39.536
So now, let's move along
and see why it went

00:06:42.330 --> 00:06:44.330
from Saint Louis to elsewhere.

00:06:44.540 --> 00:06:47.873
New York in the 19th century
was really the capital

00:06:48.510 --> 00:06:49.910
of the United States.

00:06:50.510 --> 00:06:52.310
Now, I know you're thinking
here I have come to Washington

00:06:52.510 --> 00:06:54.376
and I'm saying I'm ignorant.

00:06:54.510 --> 00:06:55.510
No, no, no.

00:06:56.510 --> 00:06:57.256
This was a swamp infested place
that only politicians went.

00:06:59.630 --> 00:07:00.690
Broadway and the music and the
theater, that was New York.

00:07:02.370 --> 00:07:04.370
Publishing, that was New York.

00:07:04.370 --> 00:07:07.036
Media, the newspapers,
that was New York.

00:07:07.350 --> 00:07:08.183
And so Pulitzer was waiting
and biding his time to get

00:07:10.050 --> 00:07:10.183
to New York and he did the same.

00:07:12.050 --> 00:07:12.653
He came to New York in 1883,
bought a bankrupt newspaper,

00:07:15.180 --> 00:07:15.233
brought his western style
of journalism to New York

00:07:18.460 --> 00:07:19.073
and became an instant success
there with a newspaper none

00:07:21.580 --> 00:07:25.313
of us know anymore because
it's gone, the New York World.

00:07:25.710 --> 00:07:28.043
And it was such a success instantly

00:07:28.220 --> 00:07:29.456
because he replicated what
he learned in Saint Louis,

00:07:30.450 --> 00:07:32.916
but he added something
very important.

00:07:33.410 --> 00:07:33.420
As an immigrant, he looked to
the lower East Side of New York

00:07:37.400 --> 00:07:40.600
and saw these vast teeming
waves of new Americans

00:07:40.780 --> 00:07:43.113
and he didn't see them as a threat.

00:07:43.680 --> 00:07:47.746
He saw them as a strength, as
something he could like himself,

00:07:47.800 --> 00:07:48.800
they're gonna contribute
to the United States.

00:07:49.800 --> 00:07:54.066
So he admonished his reporters to
go and write about their lives.

00:07:54.600 --> 00:07:55.390
So his reporters descended on the
lower East Side and wrote stories

00:07:58.210 --> 00:07:58.416
about their lives, but not
just about their lives.

00:08:01.270 --> 00:08:03.803
They were using Dickens
as their model,

00:08:04.420 --> 00:08:06.486
tell stories about their lives.

00:08:07.470 --> 00:08:11.403
So the world would come out
with a headline, "Tiny tot falls

00:08:11.460 --> 00:08:13.660
to its death as mother looks on."

00:08:14.550 --> 00:08:15.663
And on the upper reaches of Fifth
Avenue where people drink their tea

00:08:17.970 --> 00:08:19.133
with their little finger up, one
of them said, "Hey, Elizabeth,

00:08:20.940 --> 00:08:24.206
look at this sensationalistic
prattle that's going

00:08:24.290 --> 00:08:25.423
on in the paper."

00:08:26.290 --> 00:08:27.243
And they were missing the
point because if you went

00:08:28.670 --> 00:08:28.960
to the lower East Side and you
went in the Black and Tan bars

00:08:32.380 --> 00:08:32.593
or the overcrowded dining
rooms of those tenement houses,

00:08:35.900 --> 00:08:38.433
what were those families
talking about?

00:08:38.870 --> 00:08:39.390
They were indeed talking
about the children

00:08:41.150 --> 00:08:41.583
that had fallen off the
roof the night before

00:08:43.650 --> 00:08:47.450
because the tenements were so
hot, something we know today

00:08:47.670 --> 00:08:50.536
in this tent, so hot
that in order to sleep,

00:08:51.490 --> 00:08:51.693
people went to the top
floor and children sometimes

00:08:54.620 --> 00:08:57.620
at night rolled off the
roofs to their deaths.

00:08:58.350 --> 00:09:00.750
So he wasn't covering
sensationalism.

00:09:00.750 --> 00:09:00.950
He was writing about their lives.

00:09:02.750 --> 00:09:05.950
And as a result, he gave
them a newfound dignity.

00:09:07.260 --> 00:09:07.713
Now, if any of you
were to invite me home,

00:09:09.540 --> 00:09:10.830
and don't worry this is just an
analogy, you don't have to do this,

00:09:12.650 --> 00:09:13.166
I'm betting that on your
refrigerators you have a clipping,

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:18.200
a clipping of a wedding, your son

00:09:18.360 --> 00:09:18.956
and daughter's school
achievements, sports things.

00:09:21.030 --> 00:09:24.363
Those events occurred
irregardless of the clipping.

00:09:25.330 --> 00:09:29.663
The clipping, the putting it to
print gives that moment a dignity,

00:09:30.160 --> 00:09:33.693
a meaningful representation
that you cherish and keep.

00:09:34.790 --> 00:09:35.130
Well, imagine in the world
before television and radio,

00:09:38.050 --> 00:09:40.516
those stories encapsulated
their lives

00:09:41.150 --> 00:09:43.350
and gave dignity to those people.

00:09:43.640 --> 00:09:44.560
And for once, somebody was
paying attention to them.

00:09:46.120 --> 00:09:50.853
So they in return would spend their
pennies buying the paper, of course,

00:09:51.060 --> 00:09:51.270
making the New York World this
enormous success reaching a

00:09:54.650 --> 00:09:56.716
circulation of a million copies

00:09:56.750 --> 00:10:00.483
when they're only 64 million
people in the United States.

00:10:00.830 --> 00:10:01.133
&gt;&gt; So as this goes on,
there's something else

00:10:03.460 --> 00:10:05.326
that relates to their lives.

00:10:05.460 --> 00:10:05.766
The French have decided to give
us a gift, the Statue of Liberty.

00:10:09.420 --> 00:10:10.346
And if you remember your history,
the Statue of Liberty is a gift

00:10:12.760 --> 00:10:12.856
of the French people
to the American people,

00:10:15.530 --> 00:10:17.463
not of the French government.

00:10:17.710 --> 00:10:18.213
The French people had
raised the money privately

00:10:20.340 --> 00:10:22.206
and in turn we were supposed

00:10:22.340 --> 00:10:22.570
to raise the money,
but we were failing.

00:10:24.710 --> 00:10:25.146
So Pulitzer put it on the front
page of his newspaper that the money

00:10:28.740 --> 00:10:29.133
to build the pedestal for
the statue is not coming in.

00:10:31.880 --> 00:10:35.813
He editorialized and said, "We
need to bring this money in."

00:10:35.950 --> 00:10:39.683
And people everyday, poor
people, kids, came to the paper

00:10:40.610 --> 00:10:42.543
and gave a penny or a nickel.

00:10:42.610 --> 00:10:43.230
Now, it may not seem
like much but understand.

00:10:44.990 --> 00:10:45.223
Pulitzer is like a
rubber baron of that time.

00:10:47.690 --> 00:10:49.490
He's a corporate chieftain.

00:10:49.690 --> 00:10:51.203
And the poorest people on New York
were coming in and entrusting them

00:10:52.710 --> 00:10:53.183
with their pennies and nickels
for the Statue of Liberty.

00:10:55.970 --> 00:10:59.770
And in return, he was putting
their name in the newspaper.

00:11:00.060 --> 00:11:03.860
So a kid, what they called
street Arabs or street urchins,

00:11:04.230 --> 00:11:04.303
by giving the world a penny would
have his name in the same newspaper

00:11:08.690 --> 00:11:11.356
that covered the Astors,
the Vanderbilts,

00:11:11.770 --> 00:11:12.003
and all the great names in society.

00:11:13.870 --> 00:11:14.543
So the pedestal was
built with that money.

00:11:15.930 --> 00:11:16.150
The statue arrived
and it was erected

00:11:18.110 --> 00:11:20.176
with the money of these people.

00:11:21.020 --> 00:11:21.126
So Pulitzer was changing the New
York landscape by his new use

00:11:24.980 --> 00:11:28.246
of media and exemplifying
a kind of intimate trust

00:11:29.490 --> 00:11:29.830
that no institution
might have today.

00:11:31.550 --> 00:11:32.553
I don't think many of you are gonna
rush to some large corporation

00:11:34.880 --> 00:11:35.813
and give them some
change and say I trust you

00:11:36.880 --> 00:11:38.746
to keep it for some project.

00:11:38.880 --> 00:11:40.946
We have foundations in 501c3's.

00:11:41.650 --> 00:11:42.316
So there's another
change that's gonna go

00:11:43.650 --> 00:11:43.843
on that's gonna symbolize how he's
changed our lives and created--

00:11:47.790 --> 00:11:47.796
or was the midwife of
the modern mass media.

00:11:50.650 --> 00:11:50.983
His papers become such a success
it needs a new headquarters

00:11:54.250 --> 00:11:54.840
and Pulitzer's life is
becoming a dramatic change

00:11:56.860 --> 00:11:58.660
because he's falling blind.

00:11:58.860 --> 00:11:59.436
So like Beethoven who
can't hear his own music,

00:12:01.350 --> 00:12:01.370
Pulitzer can't read his own work,

00:12:03.530 --> 00:12:06.396
but he's creating this
huge media enterprise

00:12:07.150 --> 00:12:07.283
and it needs a new headquarters.

00:12:09.150 --> 00:12:09.203
So he chooses a spot in New York

00:12:11.230 --> 00:12:11.343
and this is the second
practical lesson for you.

00:12:14.250 --> 00:12:16.716
He buys a hotel called
French's Hotel.

00:12:17.830 --> 00:12:18.686
French's Hotel was a hotel on
Park Row that had thrown them

00:12:20.840 --> 00:12:23.973
out of the lobby when he
was unemployed veteran.

00:12:23.980 --> 00:12:24.246
And if you remember the old adage,

00:12:25.980 --> 00:12:28.380
"Revenge is a dish
best served cold."

00:12:28.990 --> 00:12:29.466
Twenty years later, he
comes back, buys the hotel,

00:12:31.780 --> 00:12:34.313
and tears it down for
his headquarters.

00:12:34.860 --> 00:12:39.060
Now, Park Row is significant in
another way in that time period.

00:12:39.220 --> 00:12:42.153
This is the world before
Twitter, before CNN,

00:12:43.240 --> 00:12:43.946
before any of these
kinds of communications.

00:12:45.400 --> 00:12:46.040
So if you wanted to know
who won the election,

00:12:47.760 --> 00:12:47.913
you would go down to Park
Row and on the buildings,

00:12:50.940 --> 00:12:51.906
they would have blackboards and
they would write Cleveland is ahead.

00:12:54.440 --> 00:12:54.506
Well, it wasn't just elections.

00:12:56.440 --> 00:12:58.240
Everybody went to Park Row.

00:12:58.440 --> 00:12:59.670
When America's cup was waged,
they telegraphed the results

00:13:01.010 --> 00:13:03.810
and they had small
ships that moved across.

00:13:04.340 --> 00:13:04.870
There was a boxing match
on one of the islands

00:13:06.810 --> 00:13:06.900
and they have marionettes reenacting
the fight as the telegraphs came in.

00:13:11.520 --> 00:13:12.790
Now, for those of you who are old
enough, you're gonna get this.

00:13:14.450 --> 00:13:15.450
Think about it.

00:13:16.450 --> 00:13:18.183
The crowd loved it so much
they asked the marionette crew

00:13:18.450 --> 00:13:20.050
to do it all over again.

00:13:20.450 --> 00:13:24.850
That is instant replay a century
before ABC's Wide World of Sports.

00:13:26.060 --> 00:13:29.060
So Park Row is a terrifically
important aspect

00:13:29.590 --> 00:13:30.923
of life in New York.

00:13:31.590 --> 00:13:33.056
It's the Fleet Street.

00:13:33.590 --> 00:13:35.093
It's where the Tribune was, a little
unknown newspaper called the New

00:13:36.620 --> 00:13:41.153
York Times, the Herald, and the New
York World was being built there.

00:13:41.790 --> 00:13:44.790
So he built the tallest
building on the globe.

00:13:45.200 --> 00:13:48.533
And on the top of it was
a dome that was gold leaf.

00:13:49.300 --> 00:13:53.766
And in that office was where the
editorial crew that wrote the World

00:13:53.860 --> 00:13:54.113
and produced the paper that
on Sundays was as thick

00:13:56.940 --> 00:14:00.340
as a telephone book with
things like dress patterns.

00:14:01.240 --> 00:14:05.840
The greatest invention of that time,
of course, the Color Sunday Comic

00:14:06.520 --> 00:14:09.253
or cartoon, sheet music
that you could use

00:14:10.500 --> 00:14:10.580
to play long before we had
iPods and could download music.

00:14:14.220 --> 00:14:15.290
You could buy the New York
World and get sheet music

00:14:16.550 --> 00:14:20.350
and play the newest song that
night in your home, recipes,

00:14:21.070 --> 00:14:24.070
serialization of novels,
economic instruction.

00:14:26.390 --> 00:14:26.853
So this immigrant population turned
to the World for all of this kind

00:14:30.460 --> 00:14:34.393
of instruction on Sundays and
got it for just a few pennies.

00:14:36.090 --> 00:14:36.853
So this building went up and it was
the tallest building in the world

00:14:39.860 --> 00:14:40.140
at that point on the globe, and it
was at the centerpiece of New York.

00:14:44.180 --> 00:14:48.513
So just like he was redoing the
American mass media and reshaping,

00:14:48.720 --> 00:14:49.263
and he was reshaping the New York
skyline in a way that's so symbolic

00:14:52.710 --> 00:14:55.443
that I wanna finish
telling you this tale.

00:14:55.890 --> 00:14:55.996
Imagine these immigrants now
coming to the United States

00:14:59.450 --> 00:15:01.850
in the late 19th century,
1890 or so.

00:15:03.860 --> 00:15:06.260
And folks, this isn't a casual trip.

00:15:07.520 --> 00:15:11.120
They are leaving Ukraine,
Poland, and places like that.

00:15:11.280 --> 00:15:11.813
When they say goodbye
to their parents,

00:15:13.280 --> 00:15:16.146
there's no cheap Delta
flight home next year

00:15:16.730 --> 00:15:18.730
to come home for the holidays.

00:15:18.730 --> 00:15:19.530
They probably never
see their family alive.

00:15:20.730 --> 00:15:21.246
They're gambling their last pennies
to come to this new land and try

00:15:24.680 --> 00:15:27.346
to get a foothold in
this economic dream.

00:15:27.750 --> 00:15:28.020
So they're arriving in the
New York harbor and steerage

00:15:31.080 --> 00:15:31.886
in these overcrowded ships,
and they come up to the deck

00:15:33.940 --> 00:15:34.146
and the first thing they're gonna
see is the Statue of Liberty

00:15:37.800 --> 00:15:38.013
on a pedestal erected by
the pennies and nickels

00:15:40.720 --> 00:15:40.963
of the people who came before them.

00:15:42.810 --> 00:15:43.383
Now, they may be ignorant
of the pedestal,

00:15:44.970 --> 00:15:45.266
but they knew what the
Statue of Liberty is.

00:15:47.540 --> 00:15:48.050
At that moment, they turned and
they looked at the New York skyline

00:15:51.430 --> 00:15:51.856
for the first time in their
lives and it's their first view

00:15:54.870 --> 00:15:55.063
of the world in which they are
basing their future hopes on.

00:15:58.610 --> 00:15:58.640
And if the conditions
are just right,

00:16:00.980 --> 00:16:03.446
the sun is gleaming
off the gold dome.

00:16:05.030 --> 00:16:05.416
And so the tallest building,
taller than Trinity Church,

00:16:08.310 --> 00:16:08.476
the thing that's lighting up in
the distance is not a monument

00:16:12.210 --> 00:16:16.276
to comers, not a monument to
banking or retail or agriculture.

00:16:17.800 --> 00:16:20.600
It's a monument to the
American mass media,

00:16:20.680 --> 00:16:24.546
the only constitutionally
protected business in our society

00:16:25.200 --> 00:16:25.696
and specifically, it's their first
glimpse of the World newspaper

00:16:28.970 --> 00:16:31.703
that will be their key
to economic growth,

00:16:32.380 --> 00:16:35.513
their key to learning
Americanisms of all sorts,

00:16:36.530 --> 00:16:39.330
their key to learning
the English language.

00:16:39.330 --> 00:16:40.283
He admonished, Pulitzer
admonished his reporters

00:16:41.510 --> 00:16:45.576
to write short punchy sentences
to tell everything in the form

00:16:45.590 --> 00:16:45.833
of a story because he knew who
his readers were and, of course,

00:16:49.480 --> 00:16:51.680
his interest was political power.

00:16:51.890 --> 00:16:52.663
So he hoped they would eventually
turn to the editorial page

00:16:55.050 --> 00:16:55.763
and learn his suggestions as who to
vote for, and that certainly worked.

00:16:59.070 --> 00:16:59.236
The first Democratic
president elected

00:17:01.370 --> 00:17:02.466
after the civil war was Grover
Cleveland and you can do the math.

00:17:04.540 --> 00:17:06.940
It's the paper that got him elected.

00:17:07.370 --> 00:17:11.770
So what Pulitzer left us with after
changing the New York landscape

00:17:11.810 --> 00:17:12.000
physically and changing the American
mass media is a legacy we still have

00:17:16.420 --> 00:17:19.820
today, the notion of news
at its core being a story.

00:17:22.660 --> 00:17:26.926
He would tell his reporters that
everyday I want people at dinner

00:17:27.030 --> 00:17:30.096
to say, "Did you read
that in the World today?"

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:35.333
Producers at NBC or anything are
often saying, "I want my audience

00:17:35.340 --> 00:17:36.050
to say, 'Did you see that
story today?'" And the key

00:17:38.030 --> 00:17:41.630
to that is the story and the
humanization of the story.

00:17:41.840 --> 00:17:42.813
Think of all the great
tragedies that have occurred

00:17:44.200 --> 00:17:48.133
in our modern lives, the Haiti
earthquake, famine in Africa.

00:17:48.810 --> 00:17:52.743
When you read that millions of
people are hurt by something,

00:17:52.930 --> 00:17:57.263
it becomes a number, but we're
moved to act when we read the story

00:17:57.910 --> 00:18:02.176
of the one child who's rescued
under the rubble after three days,

00:18:02.450 --> 00:18:02.490
and that's the magic that
he was leaving us with,

00:18:05.610 --> 00:18:09.343
that in our lives exist
essentially a story and the magic

00:18:09.850 --> 00:18:12.583
of the news media is
to capture that story

00:18:12.740 --> 00:18:15.140
to humanize it and to give it to us.

00:18:15.270 --> 00:18:15.323
And that's why the World grew to
be the most powerful newspaper

00:18:19.350 --> 00:18:21.883
in America where governors
in the state

00:18:22.030 --> 00:18:22.903
of Oregon would write
all the way to New York

00:18:24.090 --> 00:18:24.223
and say, "Would you endorse me?"

00:18:26.090 --> 00:18:27.783
And I bet you today that no
governor of Oregon is writing

00:18:28.130 --> 00:18:28.223
to the New York Times and
saying, "Would you endorse me?"

00:18:31.770 --> 00:18:35.570
And so what I enjoyed about
my five-year journey is it was

00:18:36.170 --> 00:18:38.036
like being an archaeologist.

00:18:38.170 --> 00:18:38.836
I was uncovering a
world we've forgotten.

00:18:40.170 --> 00:18:41.770
The World paper is gone.

00:18:42.170 --> 00:18:42.746
We now have other papers
that have replaced it.

00:18:44.660 --> 00:18:49.060
Pulitzer is remembered as a trivial
pursuit like a name of a prize,

00:18:49.580 --> 00:18:50.276
but no one can tell you what he
did and that was the joy I had

00:18:52.950 --> 00:18:54.236
in the last five years writing,
and that's the joy I've had

00:18:55.530 --> 00:18:57.930
in answering questions from readers.

00:18:57.950 --> 00:18:59.416
Now, I have some time.

00:18:59.950 --> 00:19:00.693
I timed it just right, right,
10 minutes to answer questions

00:19:03.140 --> 00:19:05.273
and there are mics on each side.

00:19:05.410 --> 00:19:05.710
And I'll try not to
take six months to come

00:19:07.910 --> 00:19:07.976
up with the appropriate answer.

00:19:09.910 --> 00:19:10.910
Thank you.

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:12.000


00:19:12.410 --> 00:19:13.410
