00:19:16.570 --> 00:19:18.103
&gt;&gt; Thank you very much.

00:19:18.570 --> 00:19:19.380
&gt;&gt; What was Pulitzer's
connection to drama, theater,

00:19:21.160 --> 00:19:23.760
and the other prizes
that have his name?

00:19:24.260 --> 00:19:24.743
&gt;&gt; What was the connection
of Pulitzer to drama,

00:19:26.910 --> 00:19:28.643
theater, and other things?

00:19:28.910 --> 00:19:29.310
Personal. Pulitzer-- there are a lot

00:19:30.910 --> 00:19:34.976
of reasons why the Pulitzer Prize
was created, one of which is

00:19:35.080 --> 00:19:35.570
that as you probably know in 1898,
he engages in the circulation

00:19:38.790 --> 00:19:39.260
of William Randolph Hearst, yellow
journalism, a pejorative term comes

00:19:42.920 --> 00:19:45.253
about and he feels stained by that.

00:19:45.970 --> 00:19:46.433
All of his major achievements
are forever linked

00:19:48.640 --> 00:19:51.840
to this awful period much
like certain presidents

00:19:51.890 --> 00:19:53.533
who might have been in office
for eight years always remembered

00:19:54.380 --> 00:19:57.646
for one little moment and
then we forget the rest.

00:19:58.050 --> 00:19:58.550
So Pulitzer created the
Pulitzer Prize in part

00:20:00.550 --> 00:20:01.133
to cleanse his reputation
and secondly, which I'll get

00:20:03.500 --> 00:20:03.676
to in a second about his belief
in journalism that changed.

00:20:07.190 --> 00:20:10.856
But the reason there were
prizes for drama, and history,

00:20:11.380 --> 00:20:15.513
and music is a personal reflection
of his love of those things.

00:20:15.770 --> 00:20:16.140
When he falls blind, he has
readers who travel with him

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:19.226
who read him novels,
he loved Dickens,

00:20:21.240 --> 00:20:23.906
who hit a personal
pianist to play music.

00:20:24.030 --> 00:20:24.566
He loved opera and he thought
these were important parts

00:20:27.160 --> 00:20:30.026
of a civilized society
to have and a reward.

00:20:30.540 --> 00:20:34.273
But back to the major prize,
Pulitzer got into journalism

00:20:35.090 --> 00:20:35.290
because he wanted political power

00:20:37.090 --> 00:20:37.510
and journalism was the other
side of that coin back.

00:20:40.070 --> 00:20:40.870
Politics and journalism
were just two sides

00:20:42.070 --> 00:20:44.470
of the same coin in
the 19th century.

00:20:44.500 --> 00:20:44.563
But as he became a publisher
and worked in journalism,

00:20:47.970 --> 00:20:48.843
he came to understand that it
was a far more important craft

00:20:51.030 --> 00:20:53.030
than personal political power.

00:20:53.030 --> 00:20:54.070
And the most important prize
as far as he was concerned

00:20:55.590 --> 00:20:56.406
and it may sound quaint today is the
Pulitzer Prize for Public Service,

00:20:59.440 --> 00:20:59.493
the notion that journalism
may be a business.

00:21:02.320 --> 00:21:03.653
Yes, you gotta pay your
employees, but at the heart

00:21:04.320 --> 00:21:08.386
of it is it's an important part
of American democratic process

00:21:08.890 --> 00:21:08.976
and that's part of the
reason for the prize.

00:21:11.670 --> 00:21:12.036
Should I-- I guess I should
take turns and go this side.

00:21:14.970 --> 00:21:15.970
Yes?

00:21:16.970 --> 00:21:18.236
&gt;&gt; You kind of responded
to my question just then,

00:21:18.970 --> 00:21:19.036
but maybe you can expand on it.

00:21:20.970 --> 00:21:22.436
There's a lot bemoaning now
about the corporate media

00:21:22.970 --> 00:21:24.970
and with the implication being

00:21:24.970 --> 00:21:26.116
that the pre-corporate media
was somehow very altruistic

00:21:27.490 --> 00:21:28.090
and just concerned
about public service.

00:21:29.490 --> 00:21:30.250
But it's always been
a business, hasn't it?

00:21:31.530 --> 00:21:31.930
And can you talk about
the difference

00:21:33.530 --> 00:21:33.730
between the corporate media today

00:21:35.530 --> 00:21:36.396
and the corporate media
in the 19th century?

00:21:37.530 --> 00:21:38.530
&gt;&gt; Certainly.

00:21:39.530 --> 00:21:41.530
They both have-- this is a
question about the corporate media

00:21:41.530 --> 00:21:41.730
in the 19th century versus today.

00:21:43.530 --> 00:21:44.463
They both have the same
concern and they have

00:21:45.530 --> 00:21:45.596
to make money in order to work.

00:21:47.530 --> 00:21:48.710
Most of the corporate media, I
think, in my commentary that engages

00:21:50.750 --> 00:21:51.376
in a greater public service
are the family-owned newspapers

00:21:53.990 --> 00:21:54.010
because those publishers
can make the decision not--

00:21:57.370 --> 00:21:57.430
that the stockholders
aren't gonna like.

00:21:59.910 --> 00:22:03.443
I'm gonna subsidize the paper
while it's losing money.

00:22:03.620 --> 00:22:03.686
And Pulitzer did that at times.

00:22:05.620 --> 00:22:05.753
When the paper was losing money,

00:22:07.620 --> 00:22:08.286
he would simply subsidize
the enterprise.

00:22:09.620 --> 00:22:10.580
But the problem, the corporate
media, family owned or not owned,

00:22:12.860 --> 00:22:14.593
and something we all face,

00:22:15.330 --> 00:22:18.663
is that news is a terrifically
expensive enterprise

00:22:19.080 --> 00:22:22.413
to take an educated soul,
send them to Afghanistan,

00:22:22.840 --> 00:22:23.040
and give us important information

00:22:24.840 --> 00:22:27.240
about the war is not
a cheap process.

00:22:27.600 --> 00:22:27.890
And now that the news media is
finding a struggle to monetize

00:22:31.310 --> 00:22:31.613
to get that income is not a
problem for the Washington Post.

00:22:34.940 --> 00:22:36.740
Yes, it isn't making money.

00:22:36.940 --> 00:22:37.596
It's a problem for us because
our society without that kind

00:22:40.150 --> 00:22:43.616
of untethered reporting will
suffer and will become--

00:22:43.710 --> 00:22:44.046
will have less and less counter
reviews as to what's going on.

00:22:47.440 --> 00:22:47.820
So the problem is they're
similar, but the diversity

00:22:50.460 --> 00:22:51.136
in the 19th century was so
much larger than it is today.

00:22:53.450 --> 00:22:54.450
Sir?

00:22:55.450 --> 00:22:56.450
&gt;&gt; Excuse me.

00:22:57.450 --> 00:22:58.650
You mentioned in passing
William Randolph Hearst.

00:22:59.450 --> 00:23:00.450
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:23:01.450 --> 00:23:01.783
&gt;&gt; And it seems to be to the extent

00:23:03.450 --> 00:23:04.383
to which Pulitzer is
remembered historically,

00:23:05.450 --> 00:23:05.576
he tends to be paired with Hearst.

00:23:07.590 --> 00:23:08.590
&gt;&gt; Correct.

00:23:09.590 --> 00:23:10.590
Yeah.

00:23:11.590 --> 00:23:13.833
&gt;&gt; Could you perhaps spend a couple
of minutes doing a little compare

00:23:13.880 --> 00:23:14.080
and contrast between the two men?

00:23:15.880 --> 00:23:16.173
&gt;&gt; Question is about
the ying and yang.

00:23:18.120 --> 00:23:18.190
William Randolph Hearst was
and I'm not belittling Hearst,

00:23:21.850 --> 00:23:22.800
but he was ultimately the
best imitator of Pulitzer.

00:23:24.300 --> 00:23:26.300
He studied Pulitzer's methods.

00:23:26.300 --> 00:23:27.633
He came to New York.

00:23:28.300 --> 00:23:29.290
He bought a newspaper that
was interestingly started

00:23:30.710 --> 00:23:31.196
by Pulitzer's younger brother
so everyday when Pulitzer opened

00:23:34.290 --> 00:23:35.103
up the Journal and realized
this competitor might put him

00:23:37.210 --> 00:23:38.426
out of business he was competing
with the work of his brother,

00:23:40.060 --> 00:23:41.860
talk about sibling rivalry.

00:23:42.240 --> 00:23:45.173
Hearst, in many ways,
outdid Pulitzer on some

00:23:47.980 --> 00:23:50.913
of the less good aspects
of their journalism,

00:23:51.030 --> 00:23:54.430
engaged in greater
sensationalism than the World did

00:23:55.490 --> 00:23:57.890
and was far more successful at that.

00:23:58.100 --> 00:23:59.030
But the key moment comes with
the Spanish-American War.

00:24:00.770 --> 00:24:05.170
I'm sure many of you heard Mr.
Thomas talking about his book today.

00:24:05.810 --> 00:24:06.160
During the Spanish-American War,
these two papers competed in a way

00:24:09.860 --> 00:24:10.563
that we've never had
that kind of competition

00:24:12.090 --> 00:24:12.356
and they began to make up stories.

00:24:14.090 --> 00:24:14.920
Now, Pulitzer was blind and
in depression over the loss

00:24:16.860 --> 00:24:16.890
of his daughter in Jekyll Island.

00:24:19.030 --> 00:24:20.126
So in New York, William Randolph
Hearst was leading his troops

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:22.460
to compete against the
World and Pulitzer was a--

00:24:24.740 --> 00:24:26.806
had troops that had no general.

00:24:27.130 --> 00:24:27.530
And they knew if the
paper collapsed,

00:24:29.130 --> 00:24:29.530
they couldn't go to work for Hearst.

00:24:31.130 --> 00:24:32.003
So every outlandish thing Hearst
did, they tried to do equally so.

00:24:34.590 --> 00:24:38.790
To give you an example, Hearst
paper had a story about a colonel

00:24:39.110 --> 00:24:39.743
that was killed in the war
with a really odd last name

00:24:42.010 --> 00:24:42.870
like Philippe [inaudible]
or something like that.

00:24:44.350 --> 00:24:44.616
The World picked up the story
and reprinted it entirely.

00:24:47.750 --> 00:24:49.343
The next day, the Journal announced
that if you look at guy's last name,

00:24:50.890 --> 00:24:53.556
it's an anagram for
"We pilfer the news."

00:24:56.750 --> 00:24:59.550
Now, when the Spanish-American
War was over

00:24:59.570 --> 00:25:00.003
and this competition was over,
Pulitzer came back to his senses

00:25:03.270 --> 00:25:03.526
and he put out an edict that
they couldn't engage in this kind

00:25:07.080 --> 00:25:09.946
of reprehensible sensationalistic
journalism

00:25:10.100 --> 00:25:12.033
but the damage had been done.

00:25:12.100 --> 00:25:12.750
So I like to give the comparison
to Sherlock Holmes and Moriarty

00:25:15.650 --> 00:25:18.116
and I hope you all
read the last story

00:25:18.400 --> 00:25:18.956
because if not I'm
giving something away.

00:25:20.510 --> 00:25:20.973
They fight in Switzerland and
they both fall to their death.

00:25:23.980 --> 00:25:25.646
History will always link.

00:25:25.980 --> 00:25:26.646
Open up any high school
history textbook.

00:25:27.980 --> 00:25:29.176
There's always Hearst and Pulitzer,
yellow journalist linked in this

00:25:31.250 --> 00:25:31.570
and Pulitzer was never
able to escape that.

00:25:33.730 --> 00:25:36.996
So all achievements I'm
telling you about are lost

00:25:37.950 --> 00:25:38.416
because Pulitzer will
always be linked

00:25:39.950 --> 00:25:42.550
as a yellow sensationalistic
journalist.

00:25:44.870 --> 00:25:45.870
Thank you.

00:25:47.690 --> 00:25:48.690
I'm sorry.

00:25:49.690 --> 00:25:50.690
Yes, sir.

00:25:51.690 --> 00:25:53.823
&gt;&gt; A few years ago when I was in
the 5th grade, I wrote a paper

00:25:53.690 --> 00:25:54.090
on Pulitzer in the Saint Louis Post.

00:25:55.690 --> 00:25:56.423
&gt;&gt; I wish I'd found
it during my research.

00:25:57.690 --> 00:25:58.956
&gt;&gt; Well, I have talked to
you at politic controls.

00:25:59.690 --> 00:26:00.090
We both used the same
little pamphlet

00:26:01.690 --> 00:26:02.090
on the history of the Post-Dispatch.

00:26:03.690 --> 00:26:04.756
Your book was better and
certainly more recent,

00:26:05.690 --> 00:26:08.090
but could you dwell
a little bit more

00:26:08.390 --> 00:26:10.790
on the relationship
with his brother?

00:26:11.010 --> 00:26:11.230
Was his brother at all successful
and do they dislike each other

00:26:14.990 --> 00:26:16.723
or just ignore each other?

00:26:16.990 --> 00:26:18.206
&gt;&gt; The question is about
Pulitzer's unknown brother Albert.

00:26:19.640 --> 00:26:20.710
Pulitzer came from a large family
in which all the children died

00:26:22.770 --> 00:26:23.366
by the time he was 13 except for
his younger brother Albert who came

00:26:26.640 --> 00:26:26.643
to the United States after
Joseph Pulitzer and just

00:26:29.970 --> 00:26:30.360
like his older brother,
he got into journalism

00:26:32.580 --> 00:26:33.053
and this really infuriated
Joseph who was quite an egomaniac

00:26:36.040 --> 00:26:37.253
that his younger brother
not only got in journalism

00:26:38.160 --> 00:26:38.360
but was doing better than he was.

00:26:40.160 --> 00:26:41.300
He started a newspaper in New
York which was nothing but gossip.

00:26:43.220 --> 00:26:43.660
It was called the chambermaid's
delight.

00:26:45.380 --> 00:26:47.313
I mean that was its nickname.

00:26:47.380 --> 00:26:47.846
But it sold copies and here
was his brother, a millionaire,

00:26:50.780 --> 00:26:51.923
publishing in New York and
he was stuck in Saint Louis

00:26:53.170 --> 00:26:53.316
with a respectable paper,
so it really bugged him.

00:26:56.290 --> 00:27:00.956
When he came to New York, he tried
to force his brother to merge papers

00:27:01.190 --> 00:27:02.190
which of course is habit
and his brother said,

00:27:03.190 --> 00:27:05.190
"Why should I merge with you?"

00:27:05.190 --> 00:27:05.323
Pulitzer stole his entire staff.

00:27:07.190 --> 00:27:08.323
It didn't matter.

00:27:09.190 --> 00:27:10.190
It continued.

00:27:11.190 --> 00:27:12.523
Albert later sold the paper
and it became the paper

00:27:13.190 --> 00:27:13.390
that William Randolph Hearst got.

00:27:15.190 --> 00:27:15.923
What was great for me
was my little moment

00:27:17.190 --> 00:27:17.856
of discovery was I
found Albert's memoirs

00:27:19.190 --> 00:27:21.723
with his granddaughter
stored in Paris.

00:27:21.820 --> 00:27:22.603
So this book is the first to be able
to offer Albert's side of the story

00:27:25.770 --> 00:27:26.343
and trust me, it's not exactly
flattering to his older brother.

00:27:29.330 --> 00:27:31.053
And any of you who have siblings
would just love this kind of aspect.

00:27:32.140 --> 00:27:32.943
I got time for one more
question and I'll answer briefly.

00:27:35.070 --> 00:27:36.670
I am watching the clock.

00:27:37.070 --> 00:27:38.203
&gt;&gt; Hi. I'm sorry.

00:27:39.070 --> 00:27:40.070
I missed--

00:27:41.070 --> 00:27:42.470
&gt;&gt; Can you come closer to
the mic so I can hear you?

00:27:43.070 --> 00:27:44.070
&gt;&gt; I'm sorry.

00:27:45.070 --> 00:27:46.870
I missed most of your
presentation, but I was just curious

00:27:47.070 --> 00:27:51.470
with newspapers versus like media
that, you know, is on television.

00:27:53.530 --> 00:27:57.396
I don't really understand why
anybody endorses a candidate.

00:27:57.550 --> 00:27:57.883
I guess I'd look at the newspaper--

00:27:59.550 --> 00:28:00.616
&gt;&gt; Why they endorse a
candidate, you're saying?

00:28:01.550 --> 00:28:02.226
&gt;&gt; Right, because I look at
it as an objective field,

00:28:04.340 --> 00:28:04.606
but I guess I'm missing something.

00:28:06.340 --> 00:28:08.206
&gt;&gt; The question is why endorse a
candidate in an objective field.

00:28:08.740 --> 00:28:10.806
This may be an issue of my age.

00:28:10.870 --> 00:28:14.270
See, when I grew up, I
learnt how to be media savvy.

00:28:14.820 --> 00:28:15.056
The front page of the
newspaper was news.

00:28:17.250 --> 00:28:21.650
The owner who owned the editorial
page expressed his or her opinion

00:28:22.400 --> 00:28:23.080
as to who would be elected and
these two things don't always agree.

00:28:26.120 --> 00:28:26.660
Any of you who've read the Wall
Street Journal wonder if the people

00:28:29.980 --> 00:28:30.733
in the editorial page are
reading the front page

00:28:32.360 --> 00:28:33.273
because the front page
may talk about, you know,

00:28:34.580 --> 00:28:35.810
how some financial bill is
gonna ruin America and you turn

00:28:37.150 --> 00:28:37.900
to the editorial page, it
says we gotta pass this bill.

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:42.133
That was much more common today.

00:28:42.690 --> 00:28:44.290
I think what's happening

00:28:44.690 --> 00:28:46.376
with broadcast is those distinctions
are becoming more blurry.

00:28:47.070 --> 00:28:47.936
Certain networks, particularly one
that might start with letter F tends

00:28:50.870 --> 00:28:55.403
to engage in what we might as older
people feel like editorialization

00:28:56.460 --> 00:28:58.926
in the reporting, and
that's a change.

00:28:58.940 --> 00:28:59.436
That's not the way the
media originally was.

00:29:01.310 --> 00:29:05.310
There was a cardinal line that
divided the editorial division

00:29:06.030 --> 00:29:06.466
from the news division and the
news division often reported stuff

00:29:09.860 --> 00:29:10.396
that the owners in the
editorial page didn't like.

00:29:12.590 --> 00:29:12.990
But I'll leave you
with this thought.

00:29:14.590 --> 00:29:19.390
A leibling said this and this is why
those folks enjoy owning newspapers.

00:29:19.980 --> 00:29:20.293
Freedom of the press,
as you remind us,

00:29:22.200 --> 00:29:24.600
belongs to those who
own the presses.

00:29:25.250 --> 00:29:26.406
And so if you ever get upset about
an editorial in the Washington Times

00:29:28.760 --> 00:29:29.006
or the Washington Post, there
is an op-ed section edited

00:29:32.180 --> 00:29:35.046
by a wonderful man, get
your voice in there,

00:29:35.080 --> 00:29:36.893
and that would have been the
thing Pulitzer would have liked

00:29:37.200 --> 00:29:37.386
because he was one
of the first people

00:29:39.480 --> 00:29:40.043
to ever publish an op-ed article,
meaning an article by an individual

00:29:43.450 --> 00:29:43.970
that appeared on the paper that
might not agree with his viewpoint.

00:29:47.330 --> 00:29:48.330
Thank you.

00:29:49.330 --> 00:29:50.393
You're a delightful group.

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:51.000


